<segment id="1" parent="1001" relname="preparation">4. Conclusions</segment>
<segment id="2" parent="1002" relname="span">In this study , we successfully developed an algorithm</segment>
<segment id="3" parent="2" relname="purpose">to estimate the leaf angle with LiDAR-derived point cloud data .</segment>
<segment id="4" parent="1003" relname="joint">The study focused on an efficient solution for leaf segmentation and estimation of the leaf angle .</segment>
<segment id="5" parent="1005" relname="span">A leaf segmentation method</segment>
<segment id="6" parent="1006" relname="span">based on k -means</segment>
<segment id="7" parent="6" relname="elaboration">coupled with an octree structure was proposed .</segment>
<segment id="8" parent="1009" relname="span">In addition , the issue of possible segmentation errors ,</segment>
<segment id="9" parent="1010" relname="span">which has been omitted in the majority of previous studies</segment>
<segment id="10" parent="9" relname="elaboration">but which potentially affects the estimation of leaf angle distribution ,</segment>
<segment id="11" parent="1008" relname="same_unit">was discussed .</segment>
<segment id="12" parent="1012" relname="span">As was shown by the presented results ,</segment>
<segment id="13" parent="1013" relname="span">using our approaches</segment>
<segment id="14" parent="13" relname="purpose">to estimate the leaf angle shows high potential .</segment>
<segment id="15" parent="1003" relname="joint">A strong agreement in the relation</segment>
<segment id="16" parent="1003" relname="joint">and fewer potential errors between the LiDAR-derived and manual measurements were discovered .</segment>
<segment id="17" parent="1003" relname="joint">High leaf curvature within the leaf classification region was considered to affect the accuracy of leaf angle estimation .</segment>
<segment id="18" parent="1018" relname="same_unit">Fortunately ,</segment>
<segment id="19" parent="1020" relname="concession">even if such a problem presents itself ,</segment>
<segment id="20" parent="1020" relname="span">our approach can flexibly change the extent of the size of the classification region</segment>
<segment id="21" parent="1021" relname="span">based on an automatic adjustment of the k -value</segment>
<segment id="22" parent="21" relname="purpose">to achieve more accurate results .</segment>
<segment id="23" parent="1024" relname="attribution">It seems likely</segment>
<segment id="24" parent="1024" relname="contrast">that depending on the range of the leaf classification region , the level of effect of leaf curvature on the leaf angle estimation is different ,</segment>
<segment id="25" parent="1025" relname="span">but there was not enough evidence</segment>
<segment id="26" parent="25" relname="purpose">to prove this here .</segment>
<segment id="27" parent="1027" relname="span">Thus , in future work , we would like to collect data from sampling trees with different curvatures</segment>
<segment id="28" parent="1028" relname="span">to discuss them</segment>
<segment id="29" parent="28" relname="purpose">for achieving higher leaf angle estimation .</segment>
<segment id="30" parent="1032" relname="span">Furthermore , due to the location of the target tree ,</segment>
<segment id="31" parent="1033" relname="span">it is difficult to use data from more than one location of LiDAR surrounding the target tree</segment>
<segment id="32" parent="31" relname="purpose">to prevent effect of leaf occlusion on reconstruction of 3D model for LAD estimation .</segment>
<segment id="33" parent="1034" relname="joint">To achieve more accurate results of LAD estimation ,</segment>
<segment id="34" parent="1034" relname="joint">future improvements will also focus on field experimental design for data collection .</segment>
<segment id="35" parent="1036" relname="attribution">Looking at our study ,</segment>
<segment id="36" parent="1036" relname="span">automatic classification was achieved</segment>
<segment id="37" parent="1038" relname="span">by specifying a different initial parameter</segment>
<segment id="38" parent="37" relname="restatement">( L )</segment>
<segment id="39" parent="1038" relname="purpose">to find the k -value .</segment>
<segment id="40" parent="1041" relname="attribution">We considered</segment>
<segment id="41" parent="1041" relname="span">that this approach is also possible for other issues</segment>
<segment id="42" parent="41" relname="elaboration">related to unsupervised classification .</segment>
<segment id="43" parent="1043" relname="same_unit">Besides , the LiDAR-derived leaf angle method may also be useful</segment>
<segment id="44" parent="1044" relname="span">in retrieving another leaf structural parameter , such as the leaf area index</segment>
<segment id="45" parent="44" relname="restatement">( LAI ) .</segment>
<segment id="46" parent="1046" relname="span">Aside from the remote sensing field ,</segment>
<segment id="47" parent="46" relname="elaboration">this method may also prove to be effective in the measurement of the leaf angle distribution in agriculture-relevant fields .</segment>
<segment id="48" parent="1047" relname="joint">A method for accurate leaf inclination estimation in small plants has already been reported .</segment>
<segment id="49" parent="1048" relname="joint">The estimation could lead to leaf area estimation and plant structural information monitoring .</segment>
<segment id="50" parent="1049" relname="joint">In combination with our proposed method ,</segment>
<segment id="51" parent="52" relname="attribution">we expect</segment>
<segment id="52" parent="1051" relname="span">that more accurate leaf inclination angle estimation can be accomplished for leaf edges , even in small plants .</segment>
<segment id="53" parent="1052" relname="span">For these reasons , the presented method has the potential</segment>
<segment id="54" parent="53" relname="purpose">to contribute to various fields , including remote sensing and agriculture .</segment>
